{
  "text": "In a recent study [CITATION_1] by our group, we found most cognitive-affective symptoms in PoTS and VVS patients are typically subclinical, without strong causative links to personality (neurosis, trait anxiety) or traumatic experience. Instead, symptoms appeared better explained by 'interoceptive' anxiety of physical sensations and dysautonomic symptoms. This was further supported by observed deficits in interoceptive accuracy and anxiogenic interpretation of interoceptive signals by PoTS and VVS patients during head-up tilt (HUT).",
